    <p>
      Instead of simple dots, I wanted the list bullets of the index of <a href="https://blog.steren.fr&quot;/">my blog</a> to be the date at which articles were written. It turns out HTML+CSS can do that easily.
    <br>
      Here is how I created a list with custom bullets, taking their value from an HTML attribute.
    </p>

    <p>The HTML markup of my index page, note the <code>year="2020"</code> attribute on the <code>&lt;li&gt;</code> element:</p>
    <pre><code>&lt;ol class="pages"&gt;
  &lt;li year="2020"&gt;
    &lt;a href="/my-article/"&gt;My article of 2020&lt;/a&gt;
  &lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;</code></pre>

    <p>And the CSS magic. we customize the bullet with <code>::marker</code> and read the HTML attribute with <code>attr()</code>.</p>
    <pre><code>.pages {
    padding-inline-start: 6ch;
  }

  .pages li::marker {
    content: attr(year) " - ";
  }</code></pre>

    <p>Here is how it displays:</p>
    <img src="https://labs.steren.fr/2020/use-value-from-html-attribute-in-list-item-bullets/steren-blog-screenshot.png" alt="Screenshot of a list with custom bullets">


    <p>You can achieve a lot with just HTML+CSS, the <a href="https://blog.steren.fr/2020/my-stack-will-outlive-yours/">stack powering this blog and my other web pages</a>.</p> 

